Based on a review on Google Play:
{noformat}
Candy Bowling Mar 7, 2020 at 8:50 PM
The app was ok but i would advise less flashes when saving for the people with more sensitive eye sight.
{noformat}

The {{BaseTool}} class modifies the {{BottomBar}} as well as the {{DrawingSurface}} directly.
As a mid-step in refactoring this application logic should be put in wrapping classes, to avoid direct usage of {{Context}} or {{Activity}}.

Bottom bar state should be removed from tools.

Offending occurences include but are not limited to:
h3. BaseTool
{code:java}
public BaseTool(Context context, ToolType toolType) { .. }
private void resetAndInitializeToolOptions() { ... }
public void hide() { ... }
public void toggleShowToolOptions() { ... }
private void dimBackground(boolean darken) { ... }
public boolean getToolOptionsAreShown() { ... }
{code}

h3. Why is this bad
* Most of our tool "unit" tests need an Activity or Context to work, therefor making them really slow
* It violates the SOLID principles
* Makes parallel testing impossible
* Tools know about their observing views and even modify and setup them, therefore making it impossible to have more than one observing view at a time

h6. References
http://misko.hevery.com/attachments/Guide-Writing%20Testable%20Code.pdf

Our tools reside as {{public static}} variables in {{PaintroidApplication}}.
We need to move them into a class owned by our activity.
This probably needs the contained classes to be refactored, so that their state can be retained.

As the {{CommandManager}} and the {{LayerModel}} are supposed to outlive the activity on configuration changes, they have to be retained in either a headless, retained fragment or a {{ViewModel}}.

Offending variables are:
h3. PaintroidApplication
{code:java}
public static DrawingSurface drawingSurface;
public static CommandManager commandManager;
public static Tool currentTool;
public static Perspective perspective;
public static LayerContracts.Model layerModel;
{code}

h6. References
https://medium.com/inloopx/using-android-fragments-in-2018-b9cf0b05b718
https://developer.android.com/topic/libraries/architecture/viewmodel
http://misko.hevery.com/attachments/Guide-Writing%20Testable%20Code.pdf

h3. This Ticket has been split up in separate sub tickets


All our tools use application logic classes ({{Context}}, {{Activity}}, etc.) by using the {{BaseTool}} class.

We need to make the tools observable, ui classes should then observe and change properties of the corresponding tool classes.

Offending occurences include but are not limited to:
h3. BaseTool
{code:java}
public BaseTool(Context context, ToolType toolType) { .. }
private void resetAndInitializeToolOptions() { ... }
public void hide() { ... }
public void toggleShowToolOptions() { ... }
private void dimBackground(boolean darken) { ... }
public boolean getToolOptionsAreShown() { ... }
{code}

h3. Why is this bad
* Most of our tool "unit" tests need an Activity or Context to work, therefor making them really slow
* It violates the SOLID principles
* Makes parallel testing impossible
* Tools know about their observing views and even modify and setup them, therefore making it impossible to have more than one observing view at a time

h6. References
http://misko.hevery.com/attachments/Guide-Writing%20Testable%20Code.pdf

All our tools share public static variables by using the BaseTool class (and others).

Offenders include, but are not limited to:
h3. BaseTool
{code:java}
public static final Paint BITMAP_PAINT = new Paint();
public static final Paint CANVAS_PAINT = new Paint();
{code}
h3. PaintroidApplication
{code:java}
public static DrawingSurface drawingSurface;
public static CommandManager commandManager;
public static Tool currentTool;
public static Perspective perspective;
public static LayerContracts.Model layerModel;
public static File cacheDir;
public static Bitmap checkeredBackgroundBitmap;
{code}
h3. Why is this bad
 * This complicates testing a lot
 * It violates the SOLID principles
 * Makes parallel testing impossible
 * Leads to problems and crashes when starting a second MainActivity

After the refactoring step, there should be no access to public static variables whatsoever from Tools (except constants).
 Refactor the tools, move shared variables into a wrapper class which you hand to the tools on creation.
h6. References

[http://misko.hevery.com/attachments/Guide-Writing%20Testable%20Code.pdf]
